1 Introduction

This assignment will continue the analysis the stroke prediction data set analyzed in previous assignments. It will further look into finding the best model for prediciting a stroke, this time through the use of cross validation.

2 Materials

2.1 Data Set

The World Health Organization (WHO) has reported that the second leading causes of deaths worldwide, responsible for approximately 11% of deaths, is a stroke. Due to strokes being the cause of death for 11% of the population, this data set was created to help identify potential risk factors such as BMI, avverage glucose level, age, and smoking status, and hopefully predict a patients likelihood of having a stroke. Unfortunately, there is no further information on the collection methods of this data set or who collected the data.

url="https://ChloeWinters79.github.io/STA321/Data/healthcare-dataset-stroke-data.csv"
stroke.0 = read.csv(url, header = TRUE)

The data set, called stroke prediction, has 12 variables and they are as follows

  1. id: (num) unique identifier
  2. gender: (chr) âMaleâ, âFemaleâ, âOtherâ
  3. age: (num) Age (Years)
  4. hypertension: (int) 0 = no hypertension, 1 = hypertension
  5. heart_disease: (int) 0 = no heart disease, 1 = heart disease
  6. ever_married: (chr) âNoâ, âYesâ
  7. work_type: (chr) âGovt_jobâ, âNever_workedâ, âPrivateâ, âSelf-employedâ
  8. Residence_type: (chr) âRuralâ, âUrbanâ
  9. avg_glucose_level: (num) average glucose level in blood
  10. bmi: (num) body mass index
  11. smoking_status (chr): âformerly smokedâ, ânever smokedâ, âsmokesâ, âUnknownâ
  12. stroke: (int) 0 = no stroke, 1 = stroke

Of the 12 variables inside the data set, the first is ID which is a numerical variable but not one important in this analysis, there are 5 character variables, 3 binary response variables, and 3 numerical variables that are important to the analysis.

2.2 Data Cleaning

After reading in the data set, it was discovered that BMI was listed as a character variable due to the missing values being manually entered in as âN/Aâ. To correct this, all observations with a BMI of âN/Aâ were removed from the data set and BMI was converted into a numerical variable. The removable of these observations resulted in a removal of approximately 4% of the data set. Since this removal was not a significant proportion of the data set it should not have a significant impact on the final analysis and results.

Additionally, the ID variable was moved because it would not have a statistical significance on the data and is not necessary for the analysis that will be preformed. A subset of the stroke data set was also created to contain solely the continuous numerical variables, those being, age, avg_glucose_level and bmi. The purpose of this subset is to have an easily accessible data set for when only numerical analysis needs to be run.

stroke.1 = subset(stroke.0, bmi != "N/A")
stroke.1 = subset(stroke.1, gender != "Other")
stroke.1$bmi = as.numeric(stroke.1$bmi)
stroke = subset(stroke.1, select = -c(id))
stroke$age = round(stroke$age, digits = 0)
stroke.num = subset(stroke, select = c(age, avg_glucose_level, bmi))

After undergoing the data cleaning process, we are left with a final data set that is ready for the data analysis process of this assignment.

3 Methodology & Analysis

Since the WHO has identified stroke as the second leading cause of death around the world, finding what aspects of a patients health history and lifestyle may impact the likelihood of having a stroke is very important. This assignment is going to use binary predictive modeling with the use of the logistic regression model to determine the best model for predicting strokes from this data set.

3.1 Variable Analysis & Transformation

First, it is important to start with a pairwise scatter plot of the numerical variables to asses their distribution. In addition to assessing if they have a normal distribution and are unimodel, it is important to see if any of the variables have significant correlation. If any of the variables had a significant correlation we would need to worry about redundancy and possibly having to remove one of the variables. Additionally, if any of the variables are not unimodal and normally distributed, they may have to undergo some variable transformation.

library(psych)
pairs.panels(stroke.num[, -4], 
             method = "pearson", # correlation method
             hist.col = "cyan",
             density = TRUE,  # show density plots
             ellipses = TRUE # show correlation ellipses
             )

Looking at the plot, it seems that BMI is unimodal with a normal distribution. It appears that avg_glucose_level has a normal unimodal distribution with a small amount of outlier observations toward the right. However, the age variable does not appear to have a unimodal or normal distribution and appears to need to undergo some variable transformation before undergoing any further analysis. The variable age will be discretize as follows.

age = stroke$age

grp.age = age
grp.age[age %in% c(0:5)] = "0-5"
grp.age[age %in% c(6:15)] = "06-15"
grp.age[age %in% c(16:25)] = "16-25"

stroke$grp.age = grp.age

There does not appear to be a significant correlation between any of the three continuous numerical variables. Thus, none of the variables need to be dropped or seem to be at risk for being redundant

3.2 Data Split - Training and Testing Data

The data set will randomly be split into two subsets, the training data and the testing data. The training data will use 80% of the data and the testing data will use 20% of the data set. The training data will be used to search the candidate models in order to determine the final model using the cross-validation method. The testing data will be used to asses the final model selected with the training data.

Additionally, since the goal of this assignment is to determine which model has the best predictive performance it is not necessary to be concerned about the interpretation of the coefficients. Since the interpretation is not important, it is possible to standardize the numerical values even though standardizing the variables is not always considered best practice.

stroke$sd.glucose = (stroke$avg_glucose_level-mean(stroke$avg_glucose_level))/sd(stroke$avg_glucose_level)
stroke$sd.bmi = (stroke$bmi-mean(stroke$bmi))/sd(stroke$bmi)
sd.stroke = subset(stroke, select = -c(avg_glucose_level, bmi))
n <- dim(sd.stroke)[1]
train.n <- round(0.8*n)
train.id <- sample(1:n, train.n, replace = FALSE)
train <- sd.stroke[train.id, ]
test <- sd.stroke[-train.id, ]

After standardizing the numerical variables, BMI, and avg_glucose_level we were able to properly create the training and test data sets. These two data sets will be used in the analysis on the canidate models below.

3.3 Canidate Models

The previous assignments, introduced full and reduced models in order to set up the search for the final model. This assignment will look at a full, reduced, and final model through a step-wise variable selection. The optimal cut off for each candidate model will be determined in the cross validation process. Since this is a larger data set we can use 10 fold cross validation.

n <- dim(sd.stroke)[1]
train.n <- round(0.8*n)  
train.id <- sample(1:n, train.n, replace = FALSE)
train <- sd.stroke[train.id, ]
test <- sd.stroke[-train.id, ]

k = 10
fold.size = floor(dim(train)[1] / k)
PE1 = rep(0, k)
PE2 = rep(0, k)
PE3 = rep(0, k)

for(i in 1:k) {
  valid.id = (fold.size*(i-1)+1):(fold.size*i)
  valid = train[valid.id, ]
  train.dat = train[-valid.id, ]
  
# Full Model
  candidate01 = glm(stroke ~ gender + grp.age + hypertension + heart_disease + ever_married + work_type + Residence_type + sd.glucose + sd.bmi + smoking_status, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = train.dat)  
  
# Reduced Model
  candidate03 = glm(stroke ~ hypertension + heart_disease + sd.glucose, family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = train.dat) 

# Stepwise Model
  candidate02 = stepAIC(candidate01, scope = list(lower = formula(candidate03), upper = formula(candidate01)), direction = "forward", trace = 0)

  pred01 = predict(candidate01, newdata = valid, type = "response")
  pred02 = predict(candidate02, newdata = valid, type = "response")
  pred03 = predict(candidate03, newdata = valid, type = "response")
  
  pre.outcome01 = ifelse(as.vector(pred01) > 0.5, 1, 0)
  pre.outcome02 = ifelse(as.vector(pred02) > 0.5, 1, 0)
  pre.outcome03 = ifelse(as.vector(pred03) > 0.5, 1, 0)
  
  PE1[i] = mean(pre.outcome01 != valid$stroke)
  PE2[i] = mean(pre.outcome02 != valid$stroke)
  PE3[i] = mean(pre.outcome03 != valid$stroke)
}

avg.pe = cbind(PE1 = mean(PE1), PE2 = mean(PE2), PE3 = mean(PE3))
kable(avg.pe, caption = "Average of prediction errors of candidate models")
Average of prediction errors of candidate models
PE1 PE2 PE3
0.0423469 0.0423469 0.0420918

The selection of the final model is based on a 0.5 probability cut off. All 3 models have the same average predictive model. Model 2 is the simplest model so since it has the same predictive error as models 1 and 3, which are more complicated, it is the better model and thus it will be selected as the final model.

3.4 Final Model Selection

Since model 2 was deemed to be the best model after conducting the cross validation on all three candidate models, it is necessary to calculate the accuracy of the final model to help cement the decision that model 2 is the best of the tested canidate models and should be used as the final model.

pred02 = predict(candidate02, newdata = test, type = "response")
pred02.outcome = ifelse(pred02 > 0.5, 1, 0)  

accuracy = sum(pred02.outcome == test$stroke) / length(test$stroke) 
kable(data.frame(Accuracy = accuracy), caption = "The actual accuracy of the final model")
The actual accuracy of the final model
Accuracy
0.9572301

Using the pre-selected cut off of 0.5 the cross validation procedure identified the final model. The actual accuracy of the final model needs to be reported based on the test data, which is the data withheld from the training data set. The accuracy of the final model is 0.9541752, which is listed above.

4 Results & Conclusion

This assignment further analyzed the association between stroke and potential risk factors. Three candidate models were analyzed, one composed of all the variables in the data set, excluding id number, with grp.age replacing age, and bmi and avg_glucose_level being standardized. The second model consisted of heart_disease, hypertension, and a standardized avg_glucose_level. The third model contained the second model with the addition of the grp.age variable. All three models went through the cross validation process and had ROC curves created to determine which model should be used as the final mode.

After analyzing the results from the cross validation, and the ROC curve, it was determined that the second candidate model was the best and should be used as the final model. The final model that the best predictors for a having a stroke, were heart_disease, hypertension, and avg_glucose_level. The accuracy of the final model, was determined to be 95.42%.

5 General Discussion

As discussed in the previous assignment when creating the second candidate model, the second one was created based not on statistical significance, but real life application. The U.S Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) identifies some of the major risk factors for a stroke to be high blood pressure (hypertension), heart disease, and diabetes (avg_glucose_level). Using the information from the CDC, the three variables were put together to form a candidate model, which in this assignment ended up being the best and final model. Taking the information from the CDC into account it makes sense that this candidate model became the final model, in published research those three variables are noted as three of the most impactful aspects of someone having a stroke, so it makes sense that they would create an accurate final model.

Identifying these variables as things that can significantly impact a patients likelihood over having a stroke, because if patients suffer from high glucose, hypertension, or heart disease they can talk to their doctor. Knowing that these things put you at a higher risk allows patients and their doctors to make a plan and take preventive measures to help lessen their likelihood of having a stroke. Additionally, it makes the doctor and patient more aware of the possibility of a stroke allowing for the patient to be monitored and for strokes to be caught early if the patient was to have one. Being able to monitor patients and get them on a treatment plan that will lessen their likelihood of stroke can help save lives so it is important that research is constantly done and the high risk groups are being properly identified and treated.
